# break

`break` ends execution of the current loop (for, foreach, while, do-while, or switch).

```php
for ($i = 0; $i < 10; $i++) {
    if ($i == 5) {
        break; // stops loop at i=5
    }
    echo $i;
}
// Output: 01234
```

# continue

`continue` skips the rest of the current loop iteration and jumps to the next.

```php
for ($i = 0; $i < 5; $i++) {
    if ($i == 2) {
        continue; // skip printing 2
    }
    echo $i;
}
// Output: 0134
```

```php
<?php
$numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];
foreach ($numbers as $num) {
    if ($num % 2 == 0) {
        continue; // skip even numbers
    }
    echo "$num ";
}
// Output: 1 3 5

foreach ($numbers as $num) {
    if ($num > 4) {
        break; // stop when >4
    }
    echo "$num ";
}
// Output: 1 2 3 4
?>
```

# Breaking Out of Nested Loops

`break` can take an optional numeric argument to break out of multiple loops.

```php
for ($i = 0; $i < 3; $i++) {
    for ($j = 0; $j < 3; $j++) {
        if ($i == 1 && $j == 1) {
            break 2; // breaks both loops
        }
        echo "[$i,$j] ";
    }
}
// Output: [0,0] [0,1] [0,2] [1,0] 
```

Similarly, `continue 2` skips to next iteration of outer loop.

